Oh... Lindsey...

490
00:36:06,790 --> 00:36:10,325
- It's a very long story.
- Get dressed, and tell me about it on the way.

491
00:36:10,420 --> 00:36:11,749
Where are we going?

492
00:36:11,839 --> 00:36:14,793
All we know is that somebody called Nick
from the Hotel Cheval.

493
00:36:14,884 --> 00:36:16,924
<i>I spoke to a friend who works there.</i>

494
00:36:17,011 --> 00:36:19,051
<i>They keep a record of every call made.</i>

495
00:36:19,139 --> 00:36:23,601
<i>She can access the computer and we can
find out what room the call came from.</i>

496
00:36:23,687 --> 00:36:25,395
What is it?

497
00:36:25,481 --> 00:36:27,521
<i>- I know this guy.
- Who?</i>

498
00:36:27,608 --> 00:36:29,067
This guy.

499
00:36:30,528 --> 00:36:32,568
You know that guy?

500
00:36:32,656 --> 00:36:34,649
Yeah, I met him.

501
00:36:34,742 --> 00:36:36,154
He was dead.

502
00:36:38,706 --> 00:36:40,746
You met a dead guy?

503
00:36:40,833 --> 00:36:42,873
Yeah.

504
00:36:42,961 --> 00:36:45,001
In a walk-in freezer.

505
00:36:48,677 --> 00:36:51,881
Bookmaker Slim Hopkins reported missing.
Police have no leads.

506
00:36:51,972 --> 00:36:53,597
Blah, blah, blah. Yada, yada...

507
00:36:53,683 --> 00:36:57,728
A spokesperson commented off the record,
"Ironic that Hopkins should go missing,

508
00:36:57,813 --> 00:37:02,642
considering he's allegedly been behind
a few disappearing acts himself."

509
00:37:05,781 --> 00:37:10,111
I think it's time you told me that story
about why you're still wearing that towel.

510
00:37:10,203 --> 00:37:12,660
- Do you mind if I get dressed first?
- (Phone rings)

511
00:37:12,749 --> 00:37:15,501
Could be my friend from the hotel. Be right back.

512
00:37:19,131 --> 00:37:20,756
Hm.

513
00:37:31,772 --> 00:37:35,224
Hey, Lindsey, I don't think it's such a good idea
that we continue to...

514
00:37:37,154 --> 00:37:39,527
Put your shoes on, Schlomo wants to see you.

515
00:37:43,245 --> 00:37:45,285
I don't know anyone named Schlomo.

516
00:37:46,374 --> 00:37:49,994
Someone named Schlomo knows you.
That is your only concern.

517
00:37:50,088 --> 00:37:51,499
Let's go.

518
00:37:51,589 --> 00:37:53,417
Like I said, I don't know...

519
00:37:55,302 --> 00:37:57,342
Aaahh... better...

520
00:37:58,389 --> 00:38:01,059
I think it's better if you let me do the talking.

521
00:38:01,142 --> 00:38:02,638
You think?

522
00:38:08,777 --> 00:38:11,399
What is it?

523
00:38:13,533 --> 00:38:14,945
He's sorry that he hit you.

524
00:38:15,036 --> 00:38:17,076
<i>- Do you always speak for him?
- Yes.</i>

525
00:38:19,249 --> 00:38:20,993
Hm.

526
00:38:21,085 --> 00:38:23,125
So, he's a mute, then.

527
00:38:23,212 --> 00:38:24,208
Not quite.

528
00:38:24,297 --> 00:38:26,337
Well, what, then?

529
00:38:26,424 --> 00:38:28,999
It's personal. You'll have to ask him.

530
00:38:29,095 --> 00:38:31,135
- Hm. How would he tell me?
- He wouldn't.

531
00:38:36,145 --> 00:38:38,138
- Hey, are we going to the...?
- No.

532
00:38:38,231 --> 00:38:40,640
- But he's right there.
- A different outfit entirely.

533
00:38:42,153 --> 00:38:44,111
<i>Right across the street from one another?</i>

534
00:38:44,197 --> 00:38:48,527
At one time they were one with one another.
And then they tried to kill one another.

535
00:38:49,662 --> 00:38:54,290
<i>And now neither man leaves
his respective tower of isolation</i>

536
00:38:54,377 --> 00:38:56,833
for fear of what the other man will do to him.

537
00:39:06,100 --> 00:39:08,140
Let me guess, all the way up?

538
00:39:11,023 --> 00:39:13,062
Penthouse.

539
00:39:20,535 --> 00:39:22,575
Gentle piano music

540
00:39:41,770 --> 00:39:44,012
You must be Mr Fisher.

541
00:39:46,609 --> 00:39:49,646
Must I? Because... that hasn't been
working out for me lately.

542
00:39:49,738 --> 00:39:52,490
- But I'm afraid you must.
- Well, if I must.

543
00:39:53,743 --> 00:39:56,200
Do you know for what reason
you've been brought here?

544
00:40:00,043 --> 00:40:01,703
For starters, I'm unlucky.

545
00:40:01,795 --> 00:40:05,793
The unlucky are nothing more than
a frame of reference for the lucky, Mr Fisher.

546
00:40:05,883 --> 00:40:08,755
You are unlucky so I may know that I am not.

547
00:40:08,846 --> 00:40:12,429
Unfortunately, the lucky never realise
they are lucky until it's too late.

548
00:40:12,517 --> 00:40:16,136
Take yourself for instance. Yesterday
you were better off than you are today,

549
00:40:16,230 --> 00:40:21,606
but it took today for you to realise it. But...
today has arrived, and it's too late, you see?

550
00:40:23,114 --> 00:40:25,107
<i>People are never happy with what they have.</i>

551
00:40:26,242 --> 00:40:29,694
They always want what they had,
or what someone else has.

552
00:40:29,788 --> 00:40:32,197
Kinda like a rabbi
who would rather be a gangster,

553
00:40:32,292 --> 00:40:34,285
a gangster who would rather be a rabbi.

554
00:40:34,378 --> 00:40:35,457
I mean, what is that?

555
00:40:35,546 --> 00:40:38,750
Some sort of grass is always greener
on the other side of the fence thing?

556
00:40:38,842 --> 00:40:42,128
<i>I mean, how do youjustify being a rabbi</i>

557
00:40:42,221 --> 00:40:44,380
and a gangster?

558
00:40:48,354 --> 00:40:50,098
I don't.

559
00:40:50,189 --> 00:40:53,274
I'm a bad man who doesn't waste time
wondering what could've been,

560
00:40:53,360 --> 00:40:55,436
when I am what could've been or not have been.

561
00:40:55,529 --> 00:40:59,315
I live on both sides of the fence,
and my grass is always green.

562
00:40:59,994 --> 00:41:02,033
Consider, Mr Fisher...

563
00:41:02,747 --> 00:41:04,656
...there are two men sitting here before you,

564
00:41:04,749 --> 00:41:07,751
and one of them you should be very afraid of.
Where's my money?

565
00:41:09,089 --> 00:41:11,924
- I've been hearing that a lot lately.
- My father used to say,

566
00:41:12,009 --> 00:41:14,714
"The first time somebody calls you a horse,
you punch him.

567
00:41:14,804 --> 00:41:17,556
The second time somebody calls you a horse,
call him a jerk.

568
00:41:17,640 --> 00:41:21,936
But the third time somebody calls you a horse,
perhaps it's time to go shopping for a saddle."

569
00:41:31,616 --> 00:41:35,450
- I don't have your money.
- This isn't like skipping out on the check.

570
00:41:35,538 --> 00:41:38,955
You owe me money.
I have interests, you owe them money.

571
00:41:39,043 --> 00:41:41,961
- I don't even know how much money I owe you.
- $33,000.

572
00:41:42,046 --> 00:41:44,454
- But I'm not Nick fisher.
- Then who the hell are you?

573
00:41:44,549 --> 00:41:47,836
I'm just a guy who was in the wrong place
at the wrong time.

574
00:41:51,225 --> 00:41:53,265
You have 48 hours to get my money.

575
00:41:53,352 --> 00:41:56,722
Saul will keep an eye on you.
In the meantime, you may go now.

576
00:42:02,990 --> 00:42:04,401
Wait, I just have one question.

577
00:42:06,035 --> 00:42:08,075
I wasn't frisked.

578
00:42:13,670 --> 00:42:17,715
I see. So, being a rabbi, a... a religious man...

579
00:42:17,800 --> 00:42:22,178
There are three things a Jew may not do
in order to save a life, including his own.

580
00:42:22,263 --> 00:42:28,268
He may not idol-worship, commit adultery,
or perform an act of premeditated murder.

581
00:42:29,022 --> 00:42:31,430
Killing you before you killed me
would have been...

582
00:42:31,525 --> 00:42:33,565
- Kosher.
- (Exhales)

583
00:42:36,741 --> 00:42:37,737
Acceptable.

584
00:42:57,683 --> 00:43:00,139
I've wired half the money
to your bank in the Caymans.

585
00:43:00,228 --> 00:43:03,480
The other half will be deposited
when our old friend is in the ground.

586
00:43:03,566 --> 00:43:05,606
Now I can expect that when?

587
00:43:10,324 --> 00:43:12,447
- Very soon.
- Good.

588
00:43:12,535 --> 00:43:15,241
So, tell me. The kid...

589
00:43:16,082 --> 00:43:18,122
<i>What do you want with him?</i>

590
00:43:20,295 --> 00:43:22,537
The kid and I have unfinished business.

591
00:43:32,477 --> 00:43:35,313
If there's one thing I know,
it's when someone is lying.

592
00:43:35,397 --> 00:43:37,641
A man in my position, it's all he has to go on.

593
00:43:39,194 --> 00:43:42,813
To know a lie when he hears it,
it's the difference between life and death -

594
00:43:42,907 --> 00:43:44,651
your own, someone else's.

595
00:43:44,743 --> 00:43:47,828
That being said, he wasn't lying.

596
00:43:49,039 --> 00:43:50,451
That's not Nick Fisher.

597
00:43:51,627 --> 00:43:52,706
I know.

598
00:44:03,517 --> 00:44:08,014
I came back here, you were gone. So,
I went to the hotel without you to see my friend.

599
00:44:08,106 --> 00:44:11,060
She says the call to Nick came from Room 1009.

600
00:44:11,151 --> 00:44:14,937
A fellow registered under the name of Smith,
if you can believe that.

601
00:44:15,031 --> 00:44:18,900
It's one of the most common names in the world,
so there's bound to be a couple of 'em.

602
00:44:18,994 --> 00:44:21,284
But I get the feeling that this ain't one of 'em.

603
00:44:21,372 --> 00:44:24,409
I get up to the tenth floor, and just as I do,

604
00:44:24,501 --> 00:44:28,417
the door to room 1009 opens
and there's our Mr Smith. In the flesh.

605
00:44:28,507 --> 00:44:33,419
So, I pretend I'm walking to the elevator instead
of coming from it and we take it down together.

606
00:44:33,513 --> 00:44:35,636
He smiles at me - thanks - I smile back.

607
00:44:36,600 --> 00:44:39,091
<i>But I have no idea who he is
but I thinkyou might,</i>

608
00:44:39,186 --> 00:44:42,521
<i>so I take a picture using my cellphone
which I thought was a total waste</i>

609
00:44:42,608 --> 00:44:45,146
cos the photos look like shit and I never use it.

610
00:44:45,236 --> 00:44:50,397
So there I am pretending to dial a number,
and taking Smith's picture - him none the wiser.

611
00:44:51,285 --> 00:44:53,444
This is Smith. Recognise him?

612
00:44:53,538 --> 00:44:54,320
No.

613
00:44:55,249 --> 00:44:59,958
I didn't think you would, but it was worth a shot.
Anyway, we take the elevator to the lobby,

614
00:45:00,046 --> 00:45:03,914
and the man who calls himself Smith
walks outside and hails himself a cab.

615
00:45:04,009 --> 00:45:05,837
So I followed him.

616
00:45:11,561 --> 00:45:14,681
<i>He went down
into an apartment building downtown.</i>

617
00:45:14,773 --> 00:45:16,932
<i>So I wait. An hour goes by.</i>

618
00:45:18,236 --> 00:45:21,403
And just when I'm getting ready to leave -
who walks outside?

619
00:45:21,490 --> 00:45:23,317
- Smith?
- You.

620
00:45:27,914 --> 00:45:28,696
Me?

621
00:45:30,668 --> 00:45:34,797
<i>You out of the same building
with two Hasidic Jews on either side of you.</i>

622
00:45:35,799 --> 00:45:37,709
Friends of yours?

623
00:45:38,761 --> 00:45:40,220
Not exactly.

624
00:45:40,305 --> 00:45:42,548
I think it's time you told me that story.

625
00:45:44,018 --> 00:45:47,186
Well, there's this guy
and they call him The Boss, right?

626
00:45:48,274 --> 00:45:51,690
And then, right across the street
there's this man they call The Rabbi.

627
00:45:51,778 --> 00:45:54,946
- Why do they call him The Rabbi?
- Because he's a rabbi.

628
00:46:02,750 --> 00:46:05,787
So now I have to "take out",
to use the vernacular,

629
00:46:05,879 --> 00:46:08,798
The Fairy, in order to scratch a debt
that isn't even mine.

630
00:46:08,883 --> 00:46:14,720
And if that's not enough, I have 48 hours to
come up with $33,000 or The Rabbi's gonna...

631
00:46:15,725 --> 00:46:17,765
I don't know who Mr Smith is.

632
00:46:18,686 --> 00:46:21,642
And the worst part about it is,
I'm not Nick Fisher.

633
00:46:22,442 --> 00:46:23,224
Ironic.

634
00:46:24,277 --> 00:46:25,986
I know, I don't even gamble.

635
00:46:26,071 --> 00:46:29,238
No, I mean the mobster having a gay son.
That's ironic.

636
00:46:32,163 --> 00:46:35,081
We are dealing with a bona fide case
of mistaken identity here.

637
00:46:35,166 --> 00:46:39,034
Things like that aren't supposed to be real.
It's like amnesia.

638
00:46:39,129 --> 00:46:43,424
Notwithstanding, here you are,
and Nick's nowhere to be found, so...

639
00:46:43,509 --> 00:46:45,800
I'd say you're fucked.

640
00:46:45,888 --> 00:46:47,881
Fucked.

641
00:46:51,478 --> 00:46:53,685
Shouldn't you be a little worried about this?

642
00:46:53,773 --> 00:46:56,062
I have Ataraxia.

643
00:46:56,150 --> 00:46:57,350
Ataraxia?

644
00:46:58,487 --> 00:47:03,731
It's a condition characterised by freedom
from worry or any other preoccupation really.

645
00:47:06,080 --> 00:47:08,405
I have to have my answer
to The Boss in the morning.

646
00:47:08,499 --> 00:47:10,540
Oh, what are you gonna say?

647
00:47:11,921 --> 00:47:14,626
What a man with two penises would say
when his tailor asks him

648
00:47:14,716 --> 00:47:17,290
- if he dresses to the right or to the left.
- What's that?

649
00:47:19,972 --> 00:47:20,886
Yes.

650
00:47:21,850 --> 00:47:23,890
I knew you had sense.

651
00:47:25,521 --> 00:47:28,392
Sense is something you have
when you have a choice.

652
00:47:28,483 --> 00:47:30,310
Sometimes.

653
00:47:30,402 --> 00:47:32,858
Sometimes it's when you know you don't.

654
00:47:34,366 --> 00:47:37,949
Nah, don't move that bishop!
It's an obvious sucker bet.

655
00:47:38,746 --> 00:47:41,320
If you don't, y-y-you can have him in four moves.

656
00:47:41,416 --> 00:47:43,824
If you do, he's gonna have you in mate in one.

657
00:47:46,840 --> 00:47:48,418
He doesn't see it.

658
00:47:48,509 --> 00:47:51,179
Wouldn't matter if he did.

659
00:47:51,262 --> 00:47:52,757
Elvis lets me win.

660
00:47:53,974 --> 00:47:56,097
<i>Everybody lets me win.</i>

661
00:47:56,894 --> 00:47:59,849
Wait a minute. You know this game?

662
00:48:07,240 --> 00:48:08,984
THE BOSS: You got three days.

663
00:48:10,786 --> 00:48:12,579
I was thinking it would take me a week.

664
00:48:12,664 --> 00:48:15,156
Oh, you were thinking that, were you?

665
00:48:15,251 --> 00:48:19,463
With all your experience killing people?
I'll tell you what.

666
00:48:21,633 --> 00:48:23,627
You win this game, you got your week.

667
00:48:28,225 --> 00:48:28,890
Hm.

668
00:48:39,448 --> 00:48:42,366
THE BOSS: So, what's the plan with Yitzchok?

669
00:48:43,828 --> 00:48:45,620
Was gonna play it by ear.

670
00:48:45,705 --> 00:48:48,874
Well, if it's all the same,
I'd write it down. It's a tough tune.

671
00:48:50,420 --> 00:48:52,497
And, by the way, he has shadows.

672
00:48:56,344 --> 00:48:58,171
Shadows?

673
00:49:02,269 --> 00:49:04,012
Bodyguards.

674
00:49:04,771 --> 00:49:06,811
With him all the time.

675
00:49:08,693 --> 00:49:10,567
Military.

676
00:49:15,660 --> 00:49:17,700
Ex-lsraeli Mossad.

677
00:49:19,164 --> 00:49:23,210
THE BOSS: They go where he goes,
round-the-clock. Ex-lsraeli Mossad.

678
00:49:23,294 --> 00:49:25,335
Ex-lsraeli Mossad.

679
00:49:27,968 --> 00:49:29,166
That doesn't sound good.

680
00:49:30,387 --> 00:49:32,629
<i>They live in the apartment next door.</i>

681
00:49:33,557 --> 00:49:35,847
He wears a panic button on a chain
around his neck.

682
00:49:35,935 --> 00:49:38,060
<i>Looks like an ordinary Star of David.</i>

683
00:49:38,940 --> 00:49:42,309
He presses that button
and, well, we all know how that ends.

684
00:49:42,402 --> 00:49:43,813
What's this?

685
00:49:44,989 --> 00:49:46,103
Oh, God! No, you didn't?

686
00:49:49,202 --> 00:49:50,947
- Get down!
- (Silenced gunshot)

687
00:49:52,665 --> 00:49:54,955
<i>Response time's gonna be
three to five seconds.</i>

688
00:49:55,711 --> 00:49:58,000
He's gonna have to hit him
when he least expects it.

689
00:49:58,088 --> 00:50:00,128
Where?

690
00:50:00,216 --> 00:50:03,053
- Where?
- The apartment.

691
00:50:04,430 --> 00:50:08,179
How do I get in his apartment?
I can't just walk in the front door.

692
00:50:08,936 --> 00:50:11,308
No, I was thinking you'd use the back door.

693
00:50:18,865 --> 00:50:20,941
Then what?

694
00:50:21,034 --> 00:50:23,276
He does the kid, I do him.

695
00:50:24,205 --> 00:50:26,778
I plant my gun. Clean, no history.

696
00:50:26,874 --> 00:50:31,040
And Yitzchok - fire a round,
get some powder burns on the hands.

697
00:50:32,424 --> 00:50:36,125
Take the clothes off- make it look like a,

698
00:50:36,220 --> 00:50:40,931
"You do me, I do you, we're both gay, the
world doesn't understand us," double suicide.

699
00:50:42,270 --> 00:50:44,097
And that's all there is to it.

700
00:50:45,231 --> 00:50:47,390
Is that all there is to it?

701
00:50:47,484 --> 00:50:49,976
Yeah. It's all there is to it.

702
00:50:58,748 --> 00:50:59,863
Peww!

703
00:51:02,878 --> 00:51:05,003
I'm not such a bad guy, you know.

704
00:51:06,717 --> 00:51:08,959
<i>Some folks have grown pretty fat off me.</i>

705
00:51:11,723 --> 00:51:13,763
Some have grown pretty dead.

706
00:51:18,357 --> 00:51:19,816
You're a conundrum, you.

707
00:51:22,153 --> 00:51:26,780
You walk in here shooting your fucking mouth off
like you don't give a fuck if it gets shot off.

708
00:51:28,077 --> 00:51:29,488
You can only kill me once.

709
00:51:37,505 --> 00:51:38,288
Checkmate.

710
00:51:44,807 --> 00:51:46,847
Nobody says I have to kill you quick.

711
00:51:50,230 --> 00:51:52,057
Cat.

712
00:51:53,150 --> 00:51:54,978
Mouse.

713
00:51:56,655 --> 00:51:58,695
You've got three days.

714
00:52:02,662 --> 00:52:04,702
Excuse me.

715
00:52:25,524 --> 00:52:27,149
Who the fuck is this guy?

716
00:52:28,153 --> 00:52:31,605
<i>Dunno. But whoever he is, he's either in
very deep shit or I don't know what,</i>

717
00:52:31,699 --> 00:52:36,576
because he's playing in the sandbox with
the Darkies, the Skullcaps and who knows who.

718
00:52:36,664 --> 00:52:40,709
Call Murph and see if he got a match
on that photo Marty snapped.

719
00:52:40,794 --> 00:52:42,870
Yes, boss.

720
00:52:42,963 --> 00:52:46,380
I want a complete rundown on this fucker.
Everything from A to Z.

721
00:52:46,468 --> 00:52:49,469
Who he is. Who does he know?
The people he knows, who do they know?

722
00:52:49,555 --> 00:52:53,055
I want to know
what the fuck he is doing in my fucking city.

723
00:53:03,197 --> 00:53:04,691
- What have you got?
- Get this.

724
00:53:04,782 --> 00:53:07,274
