01:15:27,348 --> 01:15:29,388
Oh.

960
01:15:29,475 --> 01:15:31,516
I thought you were Saul.

961
01:15:34,231 --> 01:15:36,556
People have been thinking I'm somebody else.

962
01:15:40,153 --> 01:15:42,690
Your predicament reminds me of a story.

963
01:15:42,780 --> 01:15:45,236
Hitchcock. North By Northwest.

964
01:15:46,117 --> 01:15:50,031
The movie where everybody thinks Cary Grant
is a man named George Kaplan,

965
01:15:50,121 --> 01:15:53,241
but the thing is there is no George Kaplan.
It's just a made-up name.

966
01:15:53,332 --> 01:15:55,789
But names, even made-up ones...

967
01:15:58,338 --> 01:16:00,663
...can bring about quite a bit of trouble.

968
01:16:02,675 --> 01:16:04,134
Now...

969
01:16:04,218 --> 01:16:06,460
the woman in the picture with Grant,

970
01:16:06,554 --> 01:16:09,010
<i>- her name was er...
- Eva Marie Saint.</i>

971
01:16:09,099 --> 01:16:11,969
- Oh... you know this movie.
- I know this movie.

972
01:16:12,060 --> 01:16:15,263
I took my father to see it in 1959.
His English wasn't very good,

973
01:16:15,355 --> 01:16:18,308
but boy, did he like Miss Saint.

974
01:16:18,399 --> 01:16:21,317
After the movie he turned to me and he said,
"She's a real Buick."

975
01:16:21,403 --> 01:16:24,937
You see, he couldn't pronounce
the word beauty, so he'd say Buick.

976
01:16:26,282 --> 01:16:30,196
- Caused quite a bit of confusion.
- Using the wrong name'll do that.

977
01:16:34,583 --> 01:16:36,492
Is that my money?

978
01:16:36,584 --> 01:16:37,995
This is everything I owe you.

979
01:17:12,662 --> 01:17:16,612
It's the Sabbath. You see,
we don't answer the phone on the Sabbath.

980
01:17:16,708 --> 01:17:18,581
I know.

981
01:17:18,668 --> 01:17:20,541
Normally Saul turns off the ringer.

982
01:17:20,628 --> 01:17:21,826
Saul!

983
01:17:21,921 --> 01:17:24,591
I tell you, you can't find good help these days.

984
01:17:28,594 --> 01:17:30,883
Saul's dead.

985
01:17:33,682 --> 01:17:34,964
<i>They're all dead.</i>

986
01:17:59,458 --> 01:18:01,499
Oh, I've been in this room before.

987
01:18:04,047 --> 01:18:06,086
Looks the same as it did 20 years ago.

988
01:18:07,383 --> 01:18:09,422
Somehow...

989
01:18:10,302 --> 01:18:11,713
Somehow it seems different.

990
01:18:11,804 --> 01:18:15,588
The way your car seems different
when someone else is driving it.

991
01:18:16,893 --> 01:18:20,059
Then again, it's been 20 years
since I've been in a car.

992
01:18:21,355 --> 01:18:24,523
Two decades spent behind three inches
of bulletproof glass

993
01:18:24,609 --> 01:18:29,401
due to a natural fear of high-powered rifles
and quiet... rooftops in New Jersey.

994
01:18:29,489 --> 01:18:31,528
20 years...

995
01:18:33,534 --> 01:18:36,951
...locked away in my own paranoia,
a prisoner in my own home.

996
01:18:39,457 --> 01:18:42,328
Only to be delivered to fate by a boy.

997
01:18:46,088 --> 01:18:50,418
<i>Well, Anthony, it looks as though you've won,
if such a term may be applied.</i>

998
01:18:52,845 --> 01:18:55,217
<i>If I were wearing a hat, I would take it off.</i>

999
01:18:59,310 --> 01:19:00,934
Should we get on with it, then?

1000
01:19:07,485 --> 01:19:09,524
You can keep your hat on, Schlomo.

1001
01:19:14,701 --> 01:19:18,116
Looks like we were sold a bill of goods
by the same salesman.

1002
01:19:20,706 --> 01:19:22,746
Nice speech, though.

1003
01:19:26,629 --> 01:19:28,954
I wish I was standing for it.

1004
01:19:40,018 --> 01:19:42,259
You... you brought this upon our heads.

1005
01:19:44,647 --> 01:19:48,775
- Me?
- You... you hired Goodkat to kill my son.

1006
01:19:50,736 --> 01:19:52,776
After you murdered my son?

1007
01:19:54,574 --> 01:19:57,444
- I had no hand in that.
- Oh, sure.

1008
01:19:57,535 --> 01:19:59,574
Just like in '84?

1009
01:20:00,121 --> 01:20:03,704
I suppose you had no hand in that either.
Just a finger, maybe?

1010
01:20:06,461 --> 01:20:08,500
Time's up, Rabbi.

1011
01:20:10,131 --> 01:20:13,084
Lying to a dead man's
the same as lying to yourself.

1012
01:20:17,096 --> 01:20:19,136
You were getting too big.

1013
01:20:21,017 --> 01:20:23,056
See...

1014
01:20:24,353 --> 01:20:26,476
...problem when two men are standing in a room

1015
01:20:26,563 --> 01:20:29,482
is you can only look at one of them
and they were looking at you

1016
01:20:29,567 --> 01:20:33,066
with their backs turned,
their shirt collars smiling at me.

1017
01:20:35,740 --> 01:20:37,150
Then they called you The Boss.

1018
01:20:40,244 --> 01:20:42,284
It was clear what had to be done.

1019
01:20:48,794 --> 01:20:51,629
Try and appreciate how it feels, Schlomo...

1020
01:20:54,133 --> 01:20:58,047
...to wake up in the middle of the night
with six bullets burning in your stomach.

1021
01:20:58,929 --> 01:21:01,255
Lying in a pool of your own blood and shit.

1022
01:21:05,644 --> 01:21:07,684
The dead eyes of...

1023
01:21:11,150 --> 01:21:13,771
...of your wife... staring back at you.

1024
01:21:17,573 --> 01:21:19,613
The only thing keeping you from passing out

1025
01:21:19,701 --> 01:21:22,785
is the sound of the footsteps of the man
going down the hall...

1026
01:21:24,205 --> 01:21:26,244
...looking for your son.

1027
01:21:31,462 --> 01:21:33,502
I managed to save my son, Schlomo.

1028
01:21:35,216 --> 01:21:37,255
And now...

1029
01:21:38,427 --> 01:21:40,550
...after all these years...

1030
01:21:42,472 --> 01:21:44,015
...in spite of our agreement!

1031
01:21:45,309 --> 01:21:46,934
You... you...

1032
01:21:47,019 --> 01:21:50,020
fucking backstabbing Philistine.

1033
01:21:50,940 --> 01:21:53,098
You managed to take my son away from me.

1034
01:21:54,651 --> 01:21:56,692
Well...

1035
01:21:57,947 --> 01:22:00,070
...now I've taken your son away from you.

1036
01:22:00,157 --> 01:22:03,193
I told you I had nothing to do with...

1037
01:22:12,378 --> 01:22:14,287
You haven't heard.

1038
01:22:14,380 --> 01:22:16,419
Will I?

1039
01:22:17,007 --> 01:22:20,708
Look at my face, Schlomo. Look at my smile.

1040
01:22:22,638 --> 01:22:24,346
Your son is dead.

1041
01:22:27,726 --> 01:22:29,884
Your son is dead.

1042
01:22:32,564 --> 01:22:35,186
I'm gonna kill you. Hm.

1043
01:22:37,528 --> 01:22:38,642
<i>SLEVIN: Rabbi.</i>

1044
01:22:39,947 --> 01:22:42,023
<i>Are you familiar with the Shmoo?</i>

1045
01:22:54,378 --> 01:22:56,417
Fisher.

1046
01:22:58,299 --> 01:23:00,338
Fisher, listen to me.

1047
01:23:03,178 --> 01:23:05,752
I already told you,

1048
01:23:05,848 --> 01:23:07,887
I'm not Nick Fisher.

1049
01:23:13,230 --> 01:23:15,270
Then who is Nick Fisher?

1050
01:23:21,780 --> 01:23:23,738
I think you mean, who was Nick Fisher?

1051
01:23:25,409 --> 01:23:27,283
Fisher was the answer to a question.

1052
01:23:27,369 --> 01:23:30,121
How do you get to two men
that can't be gotten to?

1053
01:23:38,088 --> 01:23:40,128
<i>You get them to come to you.</i>

1054
01:23:48,140 --> 01:23:50,678
<i>But to do that... I needed a name.</i>

1055
01:23:51,518 --> 01:23:53,677
<i>And where do you find names?</i>

1056
01:23:53,771 --> 01:23:55,846
<i>In books.</i>

1057
01:24:00,236 --> 01:24:01,813
<i>And who has books?</i>

1058
01:24:09,911 --> 01:24:11,951
<i>Well, your bookies have books.</i>

1059
01:24:13,791 --> 01:24:14,953
He's clean.

1060
01:24:15,042 --> 01:24:17,081
<i>SLEVIN: Crooked bookies...</i>

1061
01:24:17,920 --> 01:24:21,004
<i>- ... who work with big-time crooks.
- So... why are you here?</i>

1062
01:24:32,684 --> 01:24:34,428
<i>I was looking for a gambler.</i>

1063
01:24:36,062 --> 01:24:37,807
<i>One who was in both books...</i>

1064
01:24:38,566 --> 01:24:40,938
<i>... with a lot of red in the minus column.</i>

1065
01:24:41,026 --> 01:24:42,189
Got him.

1066
01:24:42,277 --> 01:24:44,317
<i>And that's when I found Nick Fisher.</i>

1067
01:24:44,946 --> 01:24:47,069
<i>A lowlife that no-one was gonna miss.</i>

1068
01:24:48,783 --> 01:24:50,160
1729.

1069
01:24:50,244 --> 01:24:52,486
Nick Fisher.

1070
01:24:52,579 --> 01:24:54,619
OK.

1071
01:25:06,343 --> 01:25:08,382
<i>GOODKAT: There was a time.</i>

1072
01:25:25,111 --> 01:25:27,733
All that was left to do was make the phone ring.

1073
01:25:48,301 --> 01:25:52,051
<i>All I had to do was pull the trigger
and wait for you to call the man</i>

1074
01:25:52,139 --> 01:25:54,464
<i>who does thejobs that no-one else wants.</i>

1075
01:25:56,602 --> 01:25:58,641
<i>THE BOSS: I want an outsider brought in.</i>

1076
01:26:00,105 --> 01:26:02,311
There's a specialist.

1077
01:26:04,526 --> 01:26:06,602
Calls himself Mr Goodkat.

1078
01:26:12,659 --> 01:26:14,698
Fine.

1079
01:26:16,413 --> 01:26:18,655
Tell him he can expect me in the morning.

1080
01:26:23,336 --> 01:26:25,376
Are you ready?

1081
01:26:25,463 --> 01:26:27,503
Yeah.

1082
01:26:30,594 --> 01:26:32,633
It's just that one last thing.

1083
01:26:41,605 --> 01:26:43,016
<i>THE BOSS: Mr Goodkat.</i>

1084
01:26:44,024 --> 01:26:45,732
It's been a long time.

1085
01:26:50,071 --> 01:26:54,734
I'm sorry to have kept you waiting, Mr Goodkat.
So I'll get right down to business.

1086
01:26:55,869 --> 01:26:59,736
Slim Hopkins, the man who ran my book,
was hit yesterday.

1087
01:27:01,458 --> 01:27:03,699
And I guess you've already heard about...

1088
01:27:05,211 --> 01:27:07,833
<i>- ... my son.
- Yes, I heard.</i>

1089
01:27:08,840 --> 01:27:10,667
I need you to sort it out for me.

1090
01:27:10,759 --> 01:27:12,467
Who's the mark?

1091
01:27:12,552 --> 01:27:14,130
Yitzchok.

1092
01:27:17,515 --> 01:27:19,141
Yitzchok, The Rabbi's son?

1093
01:27:19,226 --> 01:27:21,432
<i>You remember The Rabbi?</i>

1094
01:27:21,520 --> 01:27:23,346
I remember The Rabbi well.

1095
01:27:23,438 --> 01:27:25,063
<i>Thing is...</i>

1096
01:27:25,148 --> 01:27:27,686
it can't look like a job.

1097
01:27:28,610 --> 01:27:31,148
<i>If Yitzchok gets hit, The Rabbi will go to war.</i>

1098
01:27:33,740 --> 01:27:38,153
So... I need you to make it look like
it ain't what it is.

1099
01:27:39,704 --> 01:27:41,910
<i>Can that be done?</i>

1100
01:27:41,998 --> 01:27:43,991
Anything can be done.

1101
01:27:46,253 --> 01:27:48,625
Good. How?

1102
01:27:48,713 --> 01:27:50,872
Kansas City Shuffle.

1103
01:27:52,675 --> 01:27:54,632
I'm not familiar with the term.

1104
01:27:57,431 --> 01:27:59,589
I'll need to see Slim's books.

1105
01:27:59,683 --> 01:28:05,269
Slim's books were taken when he was hit,
but... I do keep copies.

1106
01:28:10,027 --> 01:28:12,233
What are you looking for?

1107
01:28:15,699 --> 01:28:18,368
This is our guy. Nick - 1729.

1108
01:28:19,035 --> 01:28:21,159
1729.

1109
01:28:21,246 --> 01:28:22,657
Nick Fisher.

1110
01:28:22,748 --> 01:28:23,862
Why him?

1111
01:28:25,000 --> 01:28:26,660
A loser.

1112
01:28:26,751 --> 01:28:29,040
Pick him up. Bring him here.

1113
01:28:37,596 --> 01:28:39,968
<i>GOODKAT: Still not talking to each other, huh?</i>

1114
01:28:40,056 --> 01:28:42,096
<i>Can't say that I blame you.</i>

1115
01:28:42,183 --> 01:28:44,341
- Why are you here?
- Big job.

1116
01:28:44,435 --> 01:28:47,520
I was under the impression
you no longer worked New York.

1117
01:28:47,606 --> 01:28:50,772
Like I said... very big job.

1118
01:28:50,859 --> 01:28:55,070
And you thought, as long as you're in town,
you'd drop by and see your old pal Schlomo,

1119
01:28:55,154 --> 01:28:57,942
and say, "Hello. How about them Yanks?"

1120
01:29:00,327 --> 01:29:02,366
No. But something like that.

1121
01:29:06,541 --> 01:29:09,495
Only problem is you and I aren't old friends.

1122
01:29:09,585 --> 01:29:11,080
And I hate baseball.

1123
01:29:11,171 --> 01:29:14,456
And since we're not friends and
you hate baseball, why the fuck are you here?

1124
01:29:14,549 --> 01:29:17,420
It's because we're not friends that I'm here.

1125
01:29:18,344 --> 01:29:22,093
Because if we had been friends,
I wouldn't have been hired to kill your son.

1126
01:29:22,181 --> 01:29:26,927
Because that is right at the top of my list
of things that friends do not do to their friends.

1127
01:29:27,020 --> 01:29:30,270
The good news for you is,
my friendship is for sale.

1128
01:29:31,065 --> 01:29:34,434
You see, it seems to me
that your son means more to you alive

1129
01:29:34,527 --> 01:29:36,520
than he does to The Boss dead.

1130
01:29:36,613 --> 01:29:38,855
And more money means more to me
than less money.

1131
01:29:38,949 --> 01:29:43,076
And you are the guy that sleeps with
all that green under your mattress.

1132
01:29:43,911 --> 01:29:45,489
I'm listening.

1133
01:29:45,580 --> 01:29:49,660
You will pay me double to kill The Boss
what The Boss was paying me to kill Yitzchok.

1134
01:29:49,751 --> 01:29:52,954
- Ohh.
- And that...

1135
01:29:54,756 --> 01:29:56,795
And that will make us friends.

1136
01:29:57,592 --> 01:29:59,631
Right, Rabbi?

1137
01:30:00,721 --> 01:30:02,096
Hm?

1138
01:30:06,226 --> 01:30:10,971
And... since friends do favours for their friends,
you will do a favour for me.

1139
01:30:11,063 --> 01:30:13,982
Pray tell? What is this favour?

1140
01:30:14,067 --> 01:30:17,602
Concerns a matter of debt collection.
One debt in particular.

1141
01:30:17,695 --> 01:30:18,858
Whose?

1142
01:30:18,947 --> 01:30:22,066
A flop. From Benny's book.
Goes by the name of Nick Fisher.

1143
01:30:22,158 --> 01:30:24,316
Who is he?

1144
01:30:24,410 --> 01:30:26,450
Just a loser.

1145
01:30:26,538 --> 01:30:28,577
You just made a lot of money.

1146
01:30:32,043 --> 01:30:35,246
<i>SLEVIN: And then I was free
to come and go as I pleased.</i>

1147
01:30:49,185 --> 01:30:50,016
Hm?

1148
01:30:50,103 --> 01:30:53,187
Whatever they're paying you...

1149
01:31:00,029 --> 01:31:01,440
Oh.

1150
01:31:02,365 --> 01:31:03,610
There is nobody.

1151
01:31:05,952 --> 01:31:07,991
I did this to you.

1152
01:31:10,998 --> 01:31:12,196
- Me.
- You.

1153
01:31:12,958 --> 01:31:14,751
Me.

1154
01:31:20,883 --> 01:31:22,923
Who are you?

1155
01:31:25,596 --> 01:31:27,590
<i>BRIKOWSKl: Who is he?</i>

1156
01:31:27,682 --> 01:31:32,011
Considering he no longer has fingerprints,
I'd say it's unlikely we'll ever know.

1157
01:31:32,103 --> 01:31:33,930
What about dental records?

1158
01:31:34,021 --> 01:31:39,609
Sure, find the bottom half of the jaw, then all
we need to do is find out who the dentist was.

1159
01:31:40,445 --> 01:31:42,484
What a fucking mess.

1160
01:31:43,865 --> 01:31:46,237
<i>Hey, Brikowski, it's Marty, you there?</i>

1161
01:31:46,325 --> 01:31:50,405
<i>We found two more bodies
to go along with the two you've already got.</i>

1162
01:31:50,496 --> 01:31:52,536
All right, I'll be right over.

1163
01:31:52,624 --> 01:31:56,953
Did you ever get a hold of The Rabbi so he can
get down here and identify what's left of his kid?

1164
01:31:57,045 --> 01:32:00,413
<i>Negative.
We've been calling for the last hour, no answer.</i>

1165
01:32:00,506 --> 01:32:02,000
Send somebody over.

1166
01:32:02,091 --> 01:32:03,289
<i>Copy.</i>

1167
01:32:05,303 --> 01:32:08,138
You all right? You look a little shook-up.

1168
01:32:08,222 --> 01:32:10,096
No, I'm fine.

1169
01:32:10,183 --> 01:32:12,222
All right.

1170
01:32:35,666 --> 01:32:38,869
<i>- Yeah.
- Hey, Brikowski, it's Murphy.</i>

1171
01:32:38,961 --> 01:32:40,539
Hey, Murph, what's up?

1172
01:32:40,629 --> 01:32:43,750
<i>Harry Kello came by today.
You remember Harry?</i>

1173
01:32:43,842 --> 01:32:47,709
He retired a few years ago. His wife just died,
so he comes in a couple of times a week,

1174
01:32:47,803 --> 01:32:49,843
talks shop, tells stories to the rooks.

1175
01:32:49,930 --> 01:32:53,631
Starts every sentence with, "The way
things used to be". Guy living in the past.

1176
01:32:53,726 --> 01:32:56,300
<i>- Yeah. Yeah, what about him?
- We're making small talk.</i>

1177
01:32:56,396 --> 01:33:00,014
Guy says he can't complain,
then all he does is fuckin' complain.

1178
01:33:00,107 --> 01:33:03,523
His dead wife, the leg he got shot in,
his crappy pension,

1179
01:33:03,611 --> 01:33:07,312
but then he stops when he sees the picture
Marty snapped of your kid.

1180
01:33:07,407 --> 01:33:11,238
Just stares at it.
I say, "What is it? You know the kid?"

1181
01:33:11,327 --> 01:33:14,079
Thing is, he ain't looking at the picture,
but at the name.

1182
01:33:14,163 --> 01:33:17,579
I've got it written at the bottom.
He knows that name: Slevin.

1183
01:33:37,645 --> 01:33:39,684
I have that same phone.

1184
01:33:52,159 --> 01:33:56,537
<i>About an hour later the phone rings, it's Harry,
talking like a goddamned machine gun,</i>

1185
01:33:56,623 --> 01:33:59,113
going on and on about a horse race back in '79.

1186
01:34:02,003 --> 01:34:04,042
<i>Aqueduct.</i>

1187
01:34:05,089 --> 01:34:07,330
Seven horse, tenth race - ring a bell?

1188
01:34:08,468 --> 01:34:10,507
<i>(Race start bell)</i>

1189
01:34:15,099 --> 01:34:17,138
<i>It was a drug store handicap.</i>

1190
01:34:17,226 --> 01:34:21,271
<i>Big wind-up, around the time The Boss,
The Rabbi set up shop in New York,</i>

1191
01:34:21,356 --> 01:34:24,392
<i>before people started
waking up with knives in their backs.</i>

1192
01:34:24,484 --> 01:34:29,192
Anyway, he goes on about this local legend,
about this kid.

1193
01:34:29,280 --> 01:34:31,071
His name was Max.

1194
01:34:33,952 --> 01:34:37,735
<i>Max placed a bet with a bookie named Roth.</i>

1195
01:34:37,830 --> 01:34:40,072
Roth laid the bet off.

1196
01:34:40,166 --> 01:34:41,743
